TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Test of the Individual Action Model for Organizational Information Commons
AU  - Fulk, Janet
AU  - Heino, Rebecca
AU  - Flanagin, Andrew J.
AU  - Monge, Peter R.
AU  - Bar, François
Y1  - 2004/10/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1040.0081
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1040.0081
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 569
EP  - 585
VL  - 15
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This research elaborated and empirically tested the individual action component of the collective action model as applied to individual contributions to organizational information commons. The model extended prior theory and research by making six elaborations on the classic collective action model based on unique characteristics of information goods compared to material collective goods. The structural equation model was tested via LISREL analyses of data provided by 781 respondents in three high-tech firms who had access to corporate intranets as shared information goods. The results were highly similar across organizations and indicated that (a) level of production, information retrieval, and cost predicted the perceived value of information, (b) information value and cost predicted gain, and (c) information retrieval and gain predicted the level of individual contributions to the commons.
AB  - This research elaborated and empirically tested the individual action component of the collective action model as applied to individual contributions to organizational information commons. The model extended prior theory and research by making six elaborations on the classic collective action model based on unique characteristics of information goods compared to material collective goods. The structural equation model was tested via LISREL analyses of data provided by 781 respondents in three high-tech firms who had access to corporate intranets as shared information goods. The results were highly similar across organizations and indicated that (a) level of production, information retrieval, and cost predicted the perceived value of information, (b) information value and cost predicted gain, and (c) information retrieval and gain predicted the level of individual contributions to the commons.
