TY  - JOUR
T1  - When and How Trustworthiness Matters: Knowledge Transfer and the Moderating Effect of Causal Ambiguity
AU  - Szulanski, Gabriel
AU  - Cappetta, Rossella
AU  - Jensen, Robert J.
Y1  - 2004/10/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1040.0096
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1040.0096
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 600
EP  - 613
VL  - 15
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The recognition that better use of existing internal knowledge could enhance survival chances of organizations has spawned substantial interest in the transferability of routinized, experiential learning to additional settings within the organization. Previous research has established that trustworthiness of the source enhances such knowledge transfer. More recent work, however, suggests that this may not always be the case. Yet, little systematic attention has been paid to moderating conditions. The major purpose of this paper is to identify a moderator, causal ambiguity, which delineates the conditions as to when and how a recipient's perception of the trustworthiness of a source affects the effectiveness of the transfer of organizational practices.
AB  - The recognition that better use of existing internal knowledge could enhance survival chances of organizations has spawned substantial interest in the transferability of routinized, experiential learning to additional settings within the organization. Previous research has established that trustworthiness of the source enhances such knowledge transfer. More recent work, however, suggests that this may not always be the case. Yet, little systematic attention has been paid to moderating conditions. The major purpose of this paper is to identify a moderator, causal ambiguity, which delineates the conditions as to when and how a recipient's perception of the trustworthiness of a source affects the effectiveness of the transfer of organizational practices.
